data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core/.NET 5+. This is the central issue.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no longer needed.
3. The idiomatic replacement is **`CancellationToken` + `Task.Run`**.

### Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | Unlike `Abort()`, cancellation *requests* stopping — the work must check the token. Non-cooperative work can't be forcibly killed. |
| **`OperationCanceledException` vs `TimeoutException`** | `Task.Run` + cancellation throws `OperationCanceledException`, not `ThreadAbortException`. Map this to your `TimeoutException`. |
| **`default(T)` nullability** | Same behavior, but enable nullable analysis to catch misuse. |
| **`Task.Wait(timeout)` vs `Task.WaitAsync`** | `Task.Wait(TimeSpan)` blocks the caller. Prefer `async`/`await` with `WaitAsync` if possible. |
| **Fire-and-forget danger** | If the work ignores cancellation, it keeps running silently after timeout — a resource leak `Abort()` used to prevent. |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Synchronous wrapper — preserves original API surface.
    /// Prefer ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync when callers support async.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
            ct => Task.FromResult(work()), timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Cancellation-aware overload — preferred for new code.
    /// The work delegate receives a CancellationToken it should observe.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
            ct => Task.FromResult(work(ct)), timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Fully async, cancellation-aware entry point.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run moves work to the thread pool (same isolation as
            // the original dedicated Thread, minus the ability to Abort).
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Map cancellation-due-to-timeout → TimeoutException,
            // matching the original behavior.
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // Any other exception propagates unwrapped (no AggregateException
        // thanks to await). Add .AggregateException wrapper if callers
        // depend on that contract.
    }
}
```

### Usage Comparison

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// ── Drop-in replacement (non-cooperative, same risk as before) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeSomething(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ── Cooperative cancellation (preferred) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        foreach (var item in items)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // ← check the token
            Process(item);
        }
        return items.Count;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ── Async (best) ──
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct =>
    {
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

### If You Truly Need Hard Abort

For cases where work is uncooperative (e.g., third-party code that ignores cancellation), the only safe .NET 8 option is **process isolation**:

```csharp
// Run untrusted/uncooperative work in a child process and kill it on timeout.
using var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort()` in modern .NET — this is by design, as aborting threads caused corrupted state and unreliable finalizers.
